String-matching on `.message` is fragile — tagging errors with `Data.TaggedError` gives `Effect.catchTag` a real discriminator and removes the caught case from the error channel.

```ts
import { Effect, Fiber, Data, Duration } from "effect";

class Expired extends Data.TaggedError("Expired")<{ readonly ms: number }> {}

const doWork: Effect.Effect<number> = Effect.gen(function* () {
  yield* Effect.sleep("120 millis");
  return 7;
});

const deadline = (ms: number): Effect.Effect<never, Expired> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* Effect.sleep(Duration.millis(ms));
    return yield* Effect.fail(new Expired({ ms }));
  });

const program: Effect.Effect<number, Expired> = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const fiber = yield* Effect.fork(doWork);
  return yield* Effect.race(Fiber.join(fiber), deadline(200));
});

Effect.runPromise(Effect.either(program)).then(console.log);
```

Joining in a race lets the parent bail out while still cleanly interrupting the fibre.

```ts
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";

const clamp01 = (n: number): number => Math.max(0, Math.min(1, n));
const toPercent = (n: number): number => n * 100;
const round1 = (n: number): number => Math.round(n * 10) / 10;
const render = (n: number): string => `${n.toFixed(1)}%`;

export const formatRatio = (ratio: number): string =>
  pipe(ratio, clamp01, toPercent, round1, render);

// formatRatio(0.12345) === "12.3%"
// formatRatio(-0.5)    === "0.0%"
// formatRatio(2)       === "100.0%"
```

Four stages, each one-line. The clamp-first stage is the reason this function is safer than a naive `${(r * 100).toFixed(1)}%` — but the pipe still reads as a single top-to-bottom recipe.

