Unlike a bare Promise, the returned `Fiber` can be interrupted at any time, freeing the resources it holds.

```ts
import { Effect } from "effect";

type FieldError = { readonly _tag: "FieldError"; readonly field: string; readonly message: string };
const fe = (field: string, message: string): FieldError => ({ _tag: "FieldError", field, message });

interface Checkout { cartId: string; totalCents: number; shippingZip: string }

type Rule = { field: string; ok: (c: Checkout) => boolean; message: string };

const rules: ReadonlyArray<Rule> = [
  { field: "cartId", ok: (c) => /^cart_[a-z0-9]+$/.test(c.cartId), message: "bad id" },
  { field: "totalCents", ok: (c) => c.totalCents > 0, message: "> 0" },
  { field: "shippingZip", ok: (c) => /^\d{5}$/.test(c.shippingZip), message: "5 digits" },
];

export const validateCheckout = (
  c: Checkout
): Effect.Effect<Checkout, ReadonlyArray<FieldError>> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const [errs] = yield* Effect.partition(rules, (r) =>
      r.ok(c) ? Effect.succeed(r.field) : Effect.fail(fe(r.field, r.message))
    );
    if (errs.length > 0) return yield* Effect.fail(errs);
    return c;
  });
```

`Effect.partition(rules, fn)` never short-circuits; every rule that fails ends up in the `errors` arm, which we lift into the failure channel as a `ReadonlyArray<FieldError>`.

`Effect.acquireRelease(a, r)` returns `Effect<A, E, Scope>` — the `Scope` in `R` is the tell-tale sign that a finalizer is registered. `Effect.scoped(eff)` eliminates that `Scope` requirement by creating a fresh scope, running `eff`, then closing the scope (which runs every registered finalizer).

